1. Using Templates in OpenShift
Theory
An OpenShift Template is a parameterized resource definition that allows you to deploy applications multiple times with different values.
Instead of writing separate YAML files, you define variables (parameters) inside a template.
Example use cases:
•	Deploy the same app in dev, test, prod
•	Use different image versions
•	Use different database passwords
•	Use different replica counts
A template usually contains:
•	Deployment
•	Service
•	Route
•	ConfigMap
•	Parameters
________________________________________
Example Template Parameter
Example template variable:
parameters:
- name: APP_NAME
  value: myapp
Then used in resources:
metadata:
  name: ${APP_NAME}
During deployment you can change the value.
________________________________________
2. Upload Template to OpenShift
Command:
oc create -f template.yaml
Explanation
Part	Meaning
oc	OpenShift CLI
create	create resource
-f	file
template.yaml	template file
This uploads the template to the current project (namespace).
Example:
oc create -f wordpress-template.yaml
Now the template is available in the project.
________________________________________
3. Process a Template
Templates must be processed before deployment.
Command:
oc process template-name
Example:
oc process mysql-template
What happens?
The template engine:
1.	replaces parameters
2.	generates Kubernetes objects
3.	outputs YAML
Example output:
Deployment
Service
Route
________________________________________
4. Deploy Processed Resources
To deploy processed resources:
oc process template.yaml | oc apply -f -
Explanation
Part	Meaning
oc process	process template
	pipe output
oc apply	deploy resources
-f -	read from STDIN
Example workflow:
oc process wordpress-template | oc apply -f -
This creates all resources.
________________________________________
5. Passing Template Parameters
You can customize template parameters.
Method 1 — Using -p
Command:
oc process template.yaml -p PARAM=value
Example:
oc process wordpress-template -p APP_NAME=myblog
________________________________________
Method 2 — Using Parameter File
Command:
oc process template.yaml --param-file=params.env
Example params.env:
APP_NAME=myblog
DB_PASSWORD=secret
This is useful for large deployments.
________________________________________
6. Helm Repositories
Theory
A Helm repository stores Helm charts.
Similar to:
System	Package Repo
Linux	yum repo
Docker	container registry
Helm	chart repository
Examples:
•	ArtifactHub
•	Bitnami Helm repo
•	Red Hat Helm repo
________________________________________
Add Helm Repository
Command:
helm repo add repo-name repo-url
Example:
helm repo add do280-repo http://helm.ocp4.example.com/charts
What happens?
Helm stores repo info in:
~/.config/helm/repositories.yaml
This file contains:
repo name
repo URL
________________________________________
7. Search Helm Charts
Command:
helm search repo
Example:
helm search repo etherpad
This searches all configured repositories.
Example output:
do280-repo/etherpad
________________________________________
8. Inspect Helm Charts
Before installing a chart you should inspect it.
Helm provides two useful commands.
________________________________________
Show Chart Metadata
Command:
helm show chart chart-reference
Example:
helm show chart do280-repo/etherpad
Shows:
•	chart name
•	version
•	description
•	maintainers
•	dependencies
Example output:
name: etherpad
version: 0.0.7
description: Etherpad collaborative editor
________________________________________
Show Default Configuration
Command:
helm show values chart-reference
Example:
helm show values do280-repo/etherpad
Shows default values.yaml.
Example:
replicaCount: 1

image:
  repository: etherpad
  tag: latest
These values can be overridden using values.yaml.
________________________________________
9. Install Helm Chart
Command:
helm install release-name chart-reference
Example:
helm install myapp do280-repo/etherpad
Explanation
Part	Meaning
helm install	deploy chart
release-name	instance name
chart-reference	chart
Helm creates:
•	Deployment
•	Service
•	Route
•	ConfigMaps
•	Secrets
________________________________________
10. List Installed Releases
Command:
helm list
Example output:
NAME        NAMESPACE        CHART
example-app dev              etherpad-0.0.7
Meaning:
Field	Meaning
NAME	release name
NAMESPACE	project
CHART	chart version
________________________________________
11. View Release History
Helm tracks deployment versions.
Command:
helm history release-name
Example:
helm history example-app
Example output:
REVISION  STATUS     CHART
1         deployed   etherpad-0.0.6
2         deployed   etherpad-0.0.7
Meaning:
Revision	Meaning
1	first install
2	upgrade
This helps with rollback.
Example rollback command:
helm rollback example-app 1
________________________________________
12. OpenShift Templates vs Helm Charts
Feature	OpenShift Template	Helm
Parameterization	Yes	Yes
Package management	No	Yes
Version control	No	Yes
Release history	No	Yes
Upgrade capability	Limited	Excellent
Helm is more powerful.
________________________________________
13. Typical Deployment Workflow
Using Templates
create template
      ↓
oc process
      ↓
oc apply
      ↓
resources created
________________________________________
Using Helm
add repo
     ↓
search chart
     ↓
inspect chart
     ↓
helm install
     ↓
helm upgrade
________________________________________
14. Key Commands for EX280
Template Commands
Create template:
oc create -f template.yaml
Process template:
oc process template.yaml
Deploy template:
oc process template.yaml | oc apply -f -
Add parameters:
oc process template.yaml -p NAME=value
________________________________________
Helm Commands
Add repo:
helm repo add NAME URL
Search charts:
helm search repo
View chart:
helm show chart CHART
View values:
helm show values CHART
Install chart:
helm install RELEASE CHART
List releases:
helm list
View history:
helm history RELEASE
________________________________________
✅ Main idea of this section:
•	OpenShift Templates = parameterized manifests
•	Helm = Kubernetes package manager
•	Helm provides versioning, upgrades, and release management

